Day 20 – Missing Indicator with Imputation

Today I learned about Missing Indicator, a technique used in machine learning to explicitly inform the model about which values were originally missing.

Problem

When we fill missing values using techniques like mean or median imputation, the model loses information about whether the value was originally missing or not.

Sometimes, the fact that a value is missing itself can carry important predictive information.

Missing Indicator

The Missing Indicator creates a new binary feature that shows whether a value was missing.

0 → Value was present

1 (or True) → Value was missing


This allows the model to capture patterns related to missingness.

Workflow

1. Split dataset into train and test sets.


2. Apply SimpleImputer to fill missing values.


3. Use MissingIndicator to detect where data was originally missing.


4. Add a new feature such as Age_NA that marks missing values.


5. Train the model using both the imputed feature and the indicator feature.



Alternative Approach

Scikit-learn also allows adding the indicator directly using:

SimpleImputer(add_indicator=True)

This automatically creates the missing indicator along with imputation.

Key Insight

Sometimes missing values themselves contain useful information, and adding a missing indicator feature can help machine learning models learn better patterns.
